The Fragility of the Flat World
The world is flat!
Columnist Thomas Friedman says this. Friedman chose this provocative book title for his bestseller to make people aware of the astonishing impact of technology on the world economy.
The distance is shortening.
Geographic barriers no longer provide easy protection.
Manufacturing workers and high-tech professionals in Europe and the United States all have to face the challenges of global competition.
When Western consumers call local companies, the employees they speak with are likely far away in India.
Skeptics pointed out the limitations of Friedman's analogy.
As someone once said, the world is not flat, but "uneven."
The contour map of global economic activity shows peaks of prosperity and valleys of scarcity.
Moreover, distance has far from lost its significance.
Even neighboring countries with relatively low tariff barriers, such as Canada and the United States, engage in much more domestic trade than cross-border trade.
Seattle and Vancouver are geographically close, but Vancouver's trade with the more distant Toronto is much higher than its trade with the nearby Seattle.
Despite such criticisms, Friedman put forward an important point.
Globalization can be defined as mutual dependence among different continents; its history is as long as human history itself, witnessing migrations of races and religions, as well as trade along the ancient Silk Road between medieval Europe and Asia.
But today's globalization is different; it is developing faster and more deeply.
After the first transatlantic telegraph cable was laid in 1868, Europe and the United States could communicate within a minute.
In 1919, economist John Maynard Keynes described British people living in London ordering goods from around the world by telephone and then sitting at home waiting to receive them in the afternoon.
But Keynes, as an Englishman, was a rare exception who was wealthy.
Today, hundreds of millions of people around the world can purchase goods from all over the world at their local supermarkets.
Similarly, 20 years ago, there was an immediate global communication, but it exceeded the economic capacity of the majority of people.
Now, almost anyone can walk into an Internet café and gain access to capabilities that were once exclusively controlled by the government, multinational corporations, and a small number of individuals or organizations with large budgets.
The significant decline in computing, communication, and transportation costs has made technology increasingly widespread.
Just ten years ago, two-thirds of internet users were concentrated in the United States.
But today, the proportion of internet users in the United States accounts for less than a quarter of the global total.
Knowledge is power, and the number of people who have access to information today has reached an all-time high in human history.
Non-state entities now possess capabilities that were previously exclusively controlled by the government.
The status of the nation-state as a subject in world politics will temporarily remain unchanged, but it must learn to share this vast stage with a growing number of participants, including institutions like the Oxford Food Relief Committee, celebrities such as Bono, and transnational terrorist networks like Al-Qaeda.
But this process of flattening is reversible.
Similar situations have occurred before.
In 1914, the world economy was highly integrated, but over the next 30 years, economic interdependence among countries continuously declined.
It was not until 1970 that the global economy recovered to the level of integration it had previously achieved, and at that time, it was still heavily constrained by the Iron Curtain.
World War I was the catalyst for the reversal. During the two World Wars and one global Cold War, people witnessed a decline in economic globalization and an increase in military globalization.
This reflects deeper issues such as income inequality caused by economic development in the 19th century.
Politics failed to adapt to economic development, resulting in abnormal ideologies—fascism and communism at their peak—this pathological development concept caused the fragmentation of the nation and the world.
The welfare state system in the West after World War II created a safety net for those harmed by economic changes, encouraging them to accept the benefits brought by international economic interdependence.
Some analysts believe that China's role today is very similar to that of Germany in the 20th century.
They are rising forces troubled by domestic inequality, constantly developing toward nationalism, challenging the dominant powers, and ultimately sparking a world war that reverses the progress of economic globalization.
Although the economies of the United States and China are highly interdependent today, the economies of Britain and Germany before 1914 were no less so.
But such reasoning is not complete.
After 1900, Germany's industrial production had surpassed that of Britain.
However, even if China maintains its current high growth rate, its economy is unlikely to catch up with the United States within at least 20 years.
It is likely that non-state and transnational forces unleashed by the spread of technology pose a greater threat to the flat world.
On September 11, 2001, the number of American citizens killed in a sudden attack by a non-state network exceeded the number killed in the Japanese government's Pearl Harbor attack in 1941.
I call this phenomenon the privatization of war.
If such forces were to acquire nuclear weapons and biological materials, the world would undergo a complete transformation.
At that time, it would become more difficult for people and goods to cross national borders.
If the above-mentioned forces disrupt the oil exports from the Persian Gulf, which accounts for two-thirds of the world's oil reserves, a global economic depression similar to that of the 1930s could further strengthen the forces of protectionism.
Technology and policy are the two major driving forces of globalization.
So far, policies have further reinforced the flattening effect of technology.
As the world's largest economic entity, the United States has taken the lead in promoting policies to remove obstacles.
But the events described above may reverse this policy.
Some critics of globalization might be willing to see such an outcome.
But such outcomes, as we saw after 1914, would lead to the worst situations in two areas—namely, the reversal of the economic globalization trend in the fields of communication technology and power, while the negative consequences of military and ecological globalization would be further entrenched, such as war, terrorism, climate change, and the spread of infectious diseases.
If that's truly the case, the flat world would become a desert.
